SMILE (Ours)
references:
We first evaluate our proposed SMILE method on eight diverse open-vocabulary image classification tasks using CLIP models from HuggingFace 111https://huggingface.co/openai/clip-vit-base-patch32222https://huggingface.co/openai/clip-vit-large-patch14.
For each task, the text encoder of the pre-trained model is frozen, and only the vision encoder is fine-tuned.
Table 1 presents the requirements of different model fusion methods, highlighting that SMILE is a training-free model fusion method that does not require additional labeled samples or test-time adaptation.

We further evaluate SMILE on text generation tasks using Flan-T5-base models 333https://huggingface.co/google/flan-t5-base, which are fine-tuned on eight tasks from the GLUE benchmark (Wang et al., 2018).
We use two different fine-tuning strategies: full fine-tuning and LoRA fine-tuning with rL​o​R​A=16subscript𝑟𝐿𝑜𝑅𝐴16r_{LoRA}=16.
We present the results in Tables 4 and 5, for full fine-tuned models and LoRA fine-tuned models, respectively.
For fully fine-tuned models, SMILE consistently outperforms other fusion methods across all eight tasks. With just 1.52 times the parameters of a single model, SMILE (2: kg​a​t​e=8,k=32formulae-sequencesubscript𝑘𝑔𝑎𝑡𝑒8𝑘32k_{gate}=8,k=32) achieves 99.0% of the individual model performance with 1.52 times the parameters of a single model. In the LoRA fine-tuned scenario, SMILE maintains strong performance with minimal parameter increase (1.02 times). It achieves 99.3% of the individual model performance, significantly surpassing other multi-task model fusion methods.

In Figure 7, we present the GSM8K benchmark scores of the upscaled Mistral-7B models with varying rank of local experts k𝑘k with a constant rank of routers kg​a​t​e=8subscript𝑘𝑔𝑎𝑡𝑒8k_{gate}=8. This plot highlights the trade-offs in selecting expert rank k𝑘k for the upscaled SMILE model, where the GSM8K score generally improves as k𝑘k increases, but this improvement is more pronounced for specific expert combinations, particularly for M0;1subscript𝑀01M_{0;1} and M0;123subscript𝑀0123M_{0;123}. This suggests that the routers succeed in selecting the proper expert for math problems.
In Table 6, we compare the performance of individual models and the upscaled model on various benchmark tasks. Notably, the individual expert models show strengths in specific benchmarks, such as M1subscript𝑀1M_{1} excelling in the GSM8K benchmark and M3subscript𝑀3M_{3} in the ARC Challenge. This indicates that each expert brings specialized knowledge, which when combined, enhances the overall performance in a diverse set of tasks.
More details are in Appendix E.

Tables 7 and 8 show the performance of fine-tuned CLIP-ViT-B/32 and CLIP-ViT-L/14 models, respectively, on eight image classification tasks.
These tasks include SUN397 [Xiao et al., 2010], Cars [Krause et al., 2013], RESISC45 [Cheng et al., 2017], EuroSAT [Helber et al., 2019], SVHN [Netzer et al., 2011], GTSRB [Stallkamp et al., 2012], MNIST [LeCun et al., 1998], and DTD [Cimpoi et al., 2014].
For image classification tasks, we report the classification accuracy.
Tables 9 and 10 present the performance of Flan-T5-Base models on eight text generation tasks from GLUE benchmark [Wang et al., 2018], using full fine-tuning and LoRA fine-tuning (rL​o​R​A=16subscript𝑟𝐿𝑜𝑅𝐴16r_{LoRA}=16) respectively.
We report Spearman’s ρ𝜌\rho for STSB and exact match accuracy for other tasks.
In particular for STSB, if the text outputs can not be parsed into a valid float number, we assign a score of zero.
The datasets and fine-tuned models are accessible to the public on HuggingFace [Wolf et al., 2019a]. For further information, please consult FusionBench [Tang et al., 2024a].

Negative Transfer:
In some cases, we observe negative transfer, where fine-tuning on one task harms performance on another task. For example, in Table 7, the SVHN-tuned model performs worse on EuroSAT (9.8%) compared to the pre-trained model (46.0%).

For the SMILE models, the hyperparameter settings were as follows: kg​a​t​esubscript𝑘𝑔𝑎𝑡𝑒k_{gate} was consistently set to 8 across all experiments, while k𝑘k ranged from 8 to 512 (including 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, 256, 384, and 512), as shown in Figure 7.
Table 11 provides a more comprehensive view of the performance of individual models and various SMILE models with different k𝑘k values.
We use EleutherAI/lm-evaluation-harness [Gao et al., 2024] to evaluate the models on the four tasks: MMLU, TruthfulQA, GSM8K, and ARC Challenge.
We merge the models on host memory and evaluate them on two NVIDIA 4090 GPUs with 24GB of memory each.
